# Teres Minor

> Teres minor is the **inferior posterior rotator cuff muscle**, assisting infraspinatus in **external rotation** of the shoulder. It forms the inferior border of the **quadrilateral (quadrangular) space**.

## 🔗 Key Connections
- [[Muscular System]], [[Rotator Cuff]]
- Forms: Quadrilateral space (with teres major, long head of [[Biceps Brachii|triceps]], [[Humerus]])
- Inserts on: [[Greater Tubercle]] of [[Humerus]] (inferior facet)
- Nerve: **Axillary nerve (C5, C6)** — from posterior cord of [[Brachial Plexus]]

## 🔬 Details

| Feature | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| Origin | Upper 2/3 of lateral border of [[Scapula]] |
| Insertion | Inferior facet of [[Greater Tubercle]] of [[Humerus]] |
| Action | **External rotation** of shoulder; adduction; stabilises humeral head inferiorly |
| Nerve | **Axillary nerve** (C5–C6) |

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Quadrilateral space syndrome** — axillary nerve + posterior circumflex humeral artery compressed; shoulder pain + deltoid/teres minor weakness/atrophy
- **Hornblower's sign** — hand at mouth level, can't externally rotate; suggests teres minor + infraspinatus tear

